-- Italian Stocks Gain: Bulgari, Exor, Fiat, Mediobanca, Safilo, Benetton
-- B y   F r a n c e s c a   C i n e l l i
-- 2010-10-11T15:46:15Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-10/autogrill-eni-fiat-unicredit-italian-equity-market-preview.html
Italy’s benchmark  FTSE MIB Index 
rose for a fifth day, gaining 86.97, or 0.4 percent, to
20,837.71 at the 5:30 p.m. close in Milan.  The following stocks were among the most active in the
Italian market today.  Ansaldo STS SpA  (STS IM) advanced 1.1 percent to 9.76
euros, a fifth straight gain. Finmeccanica SpA’s railway-
technology unit won a contract worth 31 million euros ($43.1
million) for the Genoa subway, according to a statement
distributed by the Italian exchange.  Beni Stabili SpA  (BNS IM) rose 2.2 percent to 70 euro
cents, the highest since April 15. Banca Akros lifted its price
estimate to 80 euro cents from 75 euro cents as “Beni Stabili’s
likelihood to apply for the SIIQ law by the end of 2010 is now
close to 100 percent.”  Fonciere des Regions SA sold 23 million shares in the
company on Oct. 8. The sale allowed the French company to cut
its stake to below 51 percent, paving the way for Beni Stabili
to become a real-estate investment trust, according to
Fonciere’s statement.  Bulgari SpA  (BUL IM), the world’s third-largest jeweler,
gained 5 percent to 6.98 euros, the best performance in the FTSE
MIB Index. Cie. Financiere Richemont SA advanced in Zurich after
Switzerland’s largest jewelry maker had its price estimate
increased at Barclays Capital Plc.  “The scenario for the industry should be favorable as it
can rely on an easy comparative base compared with last year,”
said Gian Paolo Rivano, a fund manager at Gesti-Re SGR SpA in
Milan.  Benetton Group SpA  (BEN IM), Italy’s biggest clothing
retailer, increased 2.8 percent to 5.7 euros.  Geox SpA  (GEO IM),
the Italian shoemaker that patented ventilated soles, rose 1.8
percent to 4.21 euros.  Safilo Group SpA  (SFL IM), the world’s
second-largest maker of glasses, advanced 4 percent to 10.58
euros, after climbing 5 percent on Oct. 8.  Tod’s SpA  (TOD IM)
gained 2.1 percent to 68.27 euros adjusted for a dividend per
share of 3.5 euros.  Fiat SpA  (F IM) rose for a third day, gaining 1.9 percent
to 11.42 euros. CNH Global NV, the agricultural machinery maker
controlled by Fiat, jumped 8.5 percent on Oct. 8 after the U.S.
Department of Agriculture cut its corn crop estimate.  Alfredo Altavilla, head of Fiat’s powertrain division, will
replace Paolo Monferino as chief executive officer of the Iveco
truck unit that’s being spun off from Italy’s largest
manufacturer.  Exor SpA  (EXO IM), Fiat’s main shareholder, climbed 4
percent to 17.5 euros.  Mediobanca SpA  (MB IM) advanced 1.9 percent to 7.04 euros,
the highest since Aug. 4. Italy’s largest investment bank
forecast higher net income in fiscal 2011, Il Sole 24 Ore
reported on Oct. 9, citing a company document.  Earnings “may have a positive evolution,” Mediobanca said
in the document, the Italian newspaper said.  Premafin Finanziaria SpA  (PF IM) advanced 6.1 percent to
1.05 euros after increasing 13 percent last week. French
businessman Vincent Bollore may “slightly” increase his stake
in Premafin, the holding company that controls Italy’s second-
biggest insurer Fondiaria-Sai SpA, La Repubblica reported on
Oct. 9 citing Bollore.  Prysmian SpA  (PRY IM), the world’s second-biggest cable
maker, rose 2.3 percent to 14.07 euros as the Standard & Poor’s
GSCI Index of 24 raw materials rose to the highest level in two
years.  STMicroelectronics NV  (STM IM), Europe’s biggest chipmaker,
gained 1.5 percent to 5.45 euros, ending a three-day loss. Nokia
Oyj, STMicro’s main client, rose as much as 2.7 percent in
Helsinki trading after Goldman Sachs Group Inc. raised its price
target for the world’s biggest mobile-phone maker.  Unipol Gruppo Finanziario SpA  (UNI IM) advanced 1.8 percent
to 54.85 cents as shares of Italy’s fourth-biggest insurer rose
above their 20- and 50-day moving averages.  To contact the reporter on this story:
 Francesca Cinelli  in Milan at 
 fcinelli@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
David Merritt at   dmerritt1@bloomberg.net . 